description:
src/signatures.rs:100-103 — SignatureParts owns its data:

    struct SignatureParts {
        headers: String,
        signature: String,
    }

The struct is only used within parse_signature_header, which allocates new Strings via .to_string(). Since parse_signature_header takes &str and the returned SignatureParts is consumed immediately in verify_signature, the struct could borrow from the input with lifetime annotations:

    struct SignatureParts<'a> {
        headers: &'a str,  // or Cow<'a, str> for the default case
        signature: &'a str,
    }

The headers field uses a default value ('(request-target) host date digest') when missing, so it would need Cow<'a, str>. The signature field always borrows from the input.

Impact: Two unnecessary String allocations per signature verification. Minor performance, but the borrowed version better expresses the data flow.
